"""
MKT Original Commentary — Jeremiah chapters 41–45 (fill script)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-original-jeremiah-41-45-fill.py

Context: Chs 41-44 narrate the collapse of the post-fall remnant under Gedaliah,
the assassination, flight to Egypt, and the final Egyptian sermon. Ch 45 is a
retrospective oracle to Baruch placed at the end of this narrative unit.

Key translation decisions:
- 41:5: 80 northern pilgrims from Shechem/Shiloh/Samaria — northern Israel still mourning
- 41:17: Geruth Chimham near Bethlehem — Davidic geography; anti-Exodus underway
- 42:5: the solemn oath formula — "may the LORD be a true and faithful witness against us"
- 42:7: ten days before divine response — deliberate delay signals genuine discernment
- 42:10: the build/plant language echoing 1:10 and 24:6
- 42:20: hazitem et-nafshotekem — "you have been dishonest with yourselves" (reflexive deceit)
- 43:3: Baruch as scapegoat — the accusation reveals bad faith
- 43:10: Nebuchadnezzar as "my servant" (avdi) — same as 25:9 and 27:6
- 44:4: hashkem v'shaleach (rising early and sending) — the persistent-prophet formula
- 44:17-19: melekhot ha-shamayim — the queen of heaven; the women's counter-argument
- 44:26: YHWH swears by his great name — the highest possible oath form
- 45:4: same build/tear vocabulary as the commissioning in 1:10
- 45:5: the warning against seeking great things in a time of national judgment
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

JEREMIAH = {
"41": {
"1": "<p>The dating formula (<em>baḥōdeš haššĕbîʿî</em>, the seventh month) places the assassination just after the destruction of Jerusalem in the fifth month (ch. 39). Ishmael son of Nethaniah is identified as <em>mizzereʿ hammelûkâ</em> — &quot;of royal descent&quot; — which provides his motive: a rival claimant to Davidic authority eliminates the Babylonian-appointed governor. The ten men who accompany him suggest a planned political action, not a spontaneous crime. The MKT preserves &quot;of royal descent&quot; to retain the dynastic dimension of the assassination.</p>",
"2": "<p><strong>wayyāqom Yišmāʿēl ben-Nĕtanyāhû wĕhāʿăśārâ ʾănāšîm</strong> — the assassination of Gedaliah ends Israel&apos;s last chance for a viable remnant in the land. Gedaliah was of the Shaphan family (Ahikam son of Shaphan) — the family that had protected Jeremiah throughout his ministry (26:24). His death eliminates both the protective political leadership and the administrative infrastructure for covenantal life in the land. The MKT renders the action directly: &quot;struck down Gedaliah... with the sword and killed him.&quot;</p>",
"3": "<p>The wider massacre includes not only Gedaliah but &quot;all the Jews who were with Gedaliah at Mizpah&quot; and &quot;the Chaldean soldiers (<em>ʾanšê milḥāmâ mēhaKaśdîm</em>) who were there&quot; — the Babylonian military presence too. The elimination of the Babylonian garrison removes any protection the remnant had from Chaldean reprisal. Ishmael&apos;s action guarantees that the remnant cannot remain in the land safely.</p>",
"4": "<p>The secrecy of the initial period — &quot;before anyone knew of it&quot; (<em>ûbayyôm haššēnî lĕhahrōg ʾet-Gĕdalyāhû wĕʾîš lōʾ yādāʿ</em>) — implies that Ishmael contained the news for a day. This detail prepares for the narrative trap he springs on the arriving pilgrims in v.6. The one-day concealment was the tactical window for the deception.</p>",
"5": "<p><strong>ûšĕmōnîm ʾîš bāʾû miŠĕkem miŠîlô ûmiŠōmrôn</strong> — eighty men from Shechem, Shiloh, and Samaria — all cities of the former northern kingdom. That northerners come with &quot;shaved beards, torn clothing, and self-lacerations&quot; (<em>mĕgūlĕḥê zāqān ûqĕrûʿê bĕgādîm ûmitgōdĕdîm</em>) bearing grain and incense for the temple suggests they were still oriented toward Jerusalem as their cultic center despite the northern kingdom&apos;s fall in 722 BC. The MKT preserves all three cities because they demonstrate that Israelite mourning spanned both kingdoms.</p>",
"6": "<p>Ishmael&apos;s strategic deception: he goes out to meet the pilgrims <em>bākôh bēlēk</em> (weeping as he went), performing mourning to draw them in. The invitation — &quot;Come to Gedaliah son of Ahikam&quot; — is a lie that uses Gedaliah&apos;s name as bait. The MKT renders the dramatic irony of a man weeping his way to another murder by following the MT narrative exactly.</p>",
"7": "<p><strong>wayyiheî kĕbôʾām ʾel-tôk hāʿîr wayyišḥāṭēm Yišmāʿēl</strong> — the slaughter of seventy pilgrims. <em>Wayyišlīkēm ʾel-tôk habbôr</em> — he threw their bodies into the cistern. The scale of the atrocity (seventy killed, ten spared) and the method (thrown into a cistern) is the narrative nadir of post-fall Judah. The MKT follows the MT without softening: &quot;slaughtered them and cast them into a pit.&quot;</p>",
"8": "<p><strong>ʾal-tĕmîtēnû kî-yeš-lānû matmōnîm baśśādeh</strong> — ten men survive by revealing hidden stores of food. <em>Ḥiṭṭîm ûśĕʿōrîm wĕšemen ûdĕbaš</em> (wheat, barley, oil, and honey) — agricultural survival provisions. Ishmael&apos;s economic pragmatism (he spares those with resources) shows his murders were not ideologically comprehensive. The MKT preserves the four food items as a specific detail that grounds the survival in practical terms.</p>",
"9": "<p>The cistern of King Asa — <em>habbbôr ʾăšer ʿāśâ hammelek ʾĀsāʾ</em> — connects to the narrative of 1 Kgs 15:22 where Asa conscripted all Judah to fortify Mizpah against Baasha of Israel. A defensive cistern built centuries earlier to protect Judah now holds the bodies of murdered Judeans. The MKT preserves the historical note on Asa because it is the narrator&apos;s way of marking the horror: the city Asa built for Israel&apos;s protection now contains Israel&apos;s dead.</p>",
"10": "<p><strong>wayyišb Yišmāʿēl ʾet kol-šĕʾērît hāʿām</strong> — Ishmael takes captive &quot;all the rest of the people in Mizpah, including the king&apos;s daughters&quot; (<em>ʾet-bĕnôt hammelek</em>). The king&apos;s daughters are the last Davidic royalty in the land. Ishmael intends to take them to the Ammonites (Baalis king of Ammon was behind the conspiracy, 40:14), possibly as political pawns. The MKT renders &quot;king&apos;s daughters&quot; to preserve the Davidic dynastic significance.</p>",
"11": "<p>Johanan son of Kareah and the other military commanders had been warned by Ishmael&apos;s intent (40:13-14) and now respond. <em>ʾēt kol-hārāʿâ ʾăšer ʿāśâ Yišmāʿēl ben-Nĕtanyāhû</em> — hearing of all the evil Ishmael did. The rescue mission is framed as a response to evil (<em>rāʿâ</em>), using the covenant-violation vocabulary.</p>",
"12": "<p>The pursuit ends at <em>hammayyim habbĕrēkâ haggedōlâ ʾăšer-bĕGibʿôn</em> — the great pool at Gibeon. The Gibeon pool had earlier been the site of the civil conflict between Joab and Abner&apos;s forces (2 Sam 2:13). The geography carries the weight of intra-Israelite conflict. Johanan&apos;s forces &quot;caught up with him&quot; — the rescue is just in time.</p>",
"13": "<p>The captives&apos; relief on seeing Johanan: <em>wayyiśmāḥû</em> (they were overjoyed). The single word of emotional response encapsulates the shift from captivity to rescue. The MKT&apos;s &quot;they were overjoyed&quot; renders <em>wayyiśmāḥû</em> (the same root as <em>śimḥâ</em>, joy) — the covenantal joy-vocabulary reappearing in the darkest narrative section.</p>",
"14": "<p>The captives turn back (<em>wayyāšubû wayyēlĕkû ʾel-Yôḥānān</em>) — using the <em>šûb</em> (return) vocabulary. In the wider context of Jeremiah the verb <em>šûb</em> carries heavy theological weight (return/repentance). Here it is a physical return, but the word choice may be the narrator&apos;s signal that this turning back is the right direction — toward Johanan rather than toward Ammon.</p>",
"15": "<p>Ishmael escapes with eight men to the Ammonites (<em>wayŷillāṭ Yišmāʿēl... weyēlek ʾel-bĕnê ʿAmmôn</em>). His escape means he faces no earthly justice. The unresolved escape of the assassin is a narrative detail the text does not tidy up — Ishmael vanishes from the narrative as abruptly as he entered it, his crimes unpunished within the story.</p>",
"16": "<p>The survivors Johanan recovered: &quot;men of war, women, children, and court officials (<em>sārîsîm</em>), whom he brought back from Gibeon.&quot; The word <em>sārîsîm</em> (court officials, eunuchs) indicates this includes the palace infrastructure of the post-fall government. The MKT renders &quot;court officials&quot; as the best English equivalent for <em>sārîsîm</em> in this administrative context.</p>",
"17": "<p><strong>wayyēlĕkû wayyēšĕbû bĕGerût Kimhām ʾăšer ʾeṣel Bêt-Laḥem</strong> — &quot;They set out and stayed at Geruth Chimham near Bethlehem&quot;; <em>Kimhām</em> was the son of Barzillai the Gileadite (2 Sam 19:37-40) who received land near Bethlehem from David. The remnant rests on Davidic land (Bethlehem, the city of David) on their way to Egypt — the anti-Exodus direction. The MKT preserves the Bethlehem detail because it is geographically and theologically precise.</p>",
"18": "<p>The stated motive for going to Egypt: fear of Chaldean reprisal (<em>yārĕʾû mippĕnê haKaśdîm</em>). The fear is rational — Ishmael killed the Babylonian-appointed governor. But the fear drives the decision that YHWH will explicitly forbid in ch. 42. The MKT preserves the fear motive without judgment in this verse; the judgment comes in the oracle that follows.</p>"
},
"42": {
"1": "<p>The full leadership of the post-fall remnant petitions Jeremiah — all the military commanders, Johanan son of Kareah, Jezaniah son of Hoshaiah, and &quot;all the people from the least to the greatest&quot; (<em>miqāṭōn wĕʿad-gādôl</em>). The inclusivity of the assembly (military leaders + all people) parallels the formal national assemblies of the covenant-making tradition. The decision being sought has community-wide implications.</p>",
"2": "<p><strong>tippal-nāʾ taḥinnātênû lĕpānêkā wĕhitpallēl baʿădēnû</strong> — &quot;Please hear our plea for mercy and pray to the LORD your God for us.&quot; The phrase <em>ʾĕlōhêkā</em> (your God) rather than &quot;our God&quot; is notable — the remnant recognizes that Jeremiah has privileged access to YHWH. They identify YHWH as Jeremiah&apos;s God while asking for intercession. The MKT preserves &quot;your God&quot; because the pronoun reveals the community&apos;s spiritual distance.</p>",
"3": "<p>The request: <em>wĕyaggêd-lānû YHWH ʾĕlōhêkā ʾet-hadderek ʾăšer nēlek bāh</em> — &quot;Ask the LORD your God to tell us the way we should go and what we should do.&quot; The framing is obedience to divine guidance — they claim to want to know the way and then do it. This stated openness will be revealed as bad faith in 43:2-4, but in v.3 it sounds like genuine submission.</p>",
"4": "<p><strong>šāmaʿtî hinnĕnî mitpallēl ʾel-YHWH ʾĕlōhêkem</strong> — Jeremiah accepts the prophetic commission but establishes his role: he will report whatever YHWH says without holding anything back (<em>lōʾ-ʾĕkhaśśēd mikkĕm dābār</em>). The phrase &quot;I will not withhold a word from you&quot; is the prophet&apos;s commitment to full truthfulness even if the oracle is unwelcome. The MKT renders &quot;I will not keep back a single word from you.&quot;</p>",
"5": "<p><strong>YHWH yihyeh bānû lĕʿēd ʾĕmet wĕneʾĕmān</strong> — &quot;May the LORD be a true and faithful witness against us if we do not act in accordance with all that the LORD your God sends you to tell us.&quot; The oath-formula invokes YHWH as witness-judge. <em>ʾĔmet wĕneʾĕmān</em> (true and faithful) — the covenant-reliability doublet. The oath against themselves (<em>ʾim-lōʾ nĕʿăśeh</em>) is solemn and self-binding. The MKT renders the full conditional oath: &quot;may the LORD be a true and faithful witness against us.&quot;</p>",
"6": "<p><strong>ʾim-ṭôb wĕʾim-rāʿ bĕqôl YHWH ʾĕlōhênû</strong> — &quot;Whether it is good or bad, we will obey the voice of the LORD our God.&quot; The absolute commitment — good or bad outcome — appears to be the gold standard of submitted obedience (contrast Abraham&apos;s willingness to offer Isaac). The phrase <em>lĕmaʿan yîṭab-lānû</em> (so that it may go well with us) reveals the underlying motive: compliance for benefit rather than obedience as covenant relationship. The benefit-orientation will reappear in 44:17-18 (the queen of heaven argument).</p>",
"7": "<p><strong>wayhî miqṣêh ʿăśeret yāmîm</strong> — &quot;At the end of ten days the word of the LORD came.&quot; The ten-day delay is a narrative feature: YHWH does not respond immediately. This implies genuine divine deliberation (not that YHWH needed time to decide, but that the form of the oracle required waiting). The waiting period also tests the community&apos;s patience and willingness to remain oriented toward YHWH rather than making a decision independently.</p>",
"8": "<p>Jeremiah summons all the principals — military commanders, Johanan, and all the people — for the oracle delivery. The formal summoning mirrors the formal petition of vv. 1-3. The oracle is given to the whole assembly, not whispered to one leader. The MKT preserves &quot;all the people from the least to the greatest&quot; because the universal assembly formula matches the solemnity of what follows.</p>",
"9": "<p><strong>kōh-ʾāmar YHWH ʾĕlōhê Yiśrāʾēl ʾăšer šĕlaḥtem ʾōtî ʾēlāyw lĕhapîl tĕḥinnatkĕkem lĕpānāyw</strong> — the oracle formula grounds the divine word in the community&apos;s own petition. YHWH responds to the prayer they brought — the oracle is responsive to human seeking. The MKT renders &quot;to whom you sent me to bring your petition&quot; to preserve the responsive character of the oracle.</p>",
"10": "<p><strong>ʾim-šôb tēšĕbû bāʾārets hazzōʾt ûbānîtî ʾetkem wĕlōʾ ʾehĕrōs</strong> — &quot;If you will remain in this land, I will build you up and not tear you down, and I will plant you and not uproot you&quot;; the build/plant promise echoes Jeremiah&apos;s commissioning (1:10) and the positive side of the fig oracle (24:6). <em>Kî niḥamtî ʾel-hārāʿâ ʾăšer ʿāśîtî lākem</em> — &quot;for I relent concerning the disaster I have brought on you&quot; (<em>niḥam</em>, the verb of divine relenting). YHWH&apos;s relenting is contingent on Israel staying in the land.</p>",
"11": "<p><strong>ʾal-tîrĕʾû mippĕnê melek Bābel ʾăšer ʾattem yĕrēʾîm mippānāyw</strong> — &quot;Do not be afraid of the king of Babylon, whom you now fear. Do not be afraid of him, declares the LORD, for I am with you to save you and deliver you from his power.&quot; The divine &quot;I am with you&quot; (<em>kî ʾittĕkem ʾānî</em>) formula — the Immanuel-presence promise — is the antidote to the fear of Babylon. The fear named in 41:18 as the reason for fleeing to Egypt is directly addressed and countered.</p>",
"12": "<p><strong>wĕnātattî lākem raḥămîm</strong> — &quot;I will show you compassion (<em>raḥămîm</em>)&quot;; the covenant-loyalty vocabulary — <em>raḥămîm</em> (womb-compassion, tender mercy) — invoked as the ground for Nebuchadnezzar&apos;s own compassion. YHWH will move the Babylonian king to have mercy on them and allow their return to the land. The MKT renders &quot;I will show you compassion so that he will have compassion on you&quot; to preserve the cause-effect chain: divine compassion → human compassion.</p>",
"13": "<p>The negative conditional begins: <em>wĕʾim ʾōmĕrîm ʾattem lōʾ-nēšēb bāʾārets hazzōʾt</em> — &quot;But if you say: We will not stay in this land.&quot; The either/or structure of the oracle mirrors the covenant&apos;s two-ways pattern: blessings for obedience, curses for disobedience. The command to stay is YHWH&apos;s word through the prophet; departure is disobedience to covenant instruction.</p>",
"14": "<p><strong>lēʾmōr lōʾ kî ʾerets Miṣrayim nēbôʾ</strong> — the specific reasons the remnant gives for preferring Egypt: no war, no trumpet alarm, no hunger. All three — war, trumpet, hunger — are the covenant curses they have already experienced. Egypt is conceived as covenant-curse-free space. The tragic irony is that Jeremiah&apos;s oracle promises those exact curses will follow them to Egypt (v.16).</p>",
"15": "<p><strong>šimĕʿû dĕbar-YHWH šĕʾērît Yĕhûdâ</strong> — &quot;Hear the word of the LORD, O remnant of Judah&quot;; the address <em>šĕʾērît Yĕhûdâ</em> (remnant of Judah) occurs throughout the post-fall chapters. The remnant is addressed as a recognized theological entity — the survivors who have the possibility of becoming the continuation of the covenant community. The oracle&apos;s weight is: what you do with this word determines whether there will be a remnant.</p>",
"16": "<p><strong>hahhereb ʾăšer ʾattem yĕrēʾîm mimmennâ šām tassîg ʾetkem</strong> — &quot;Then the sword you fear will overtake you there in Egypt.&quot; The irony: what they flee from will find them where they flee to. <em>Wĕhārāʿāb ʾăšer ʾattem dōʾăgîm mimmennû šām yidbaqlākem bĕMiṣrayim</em> — &quot;and the famine you dread will pursue you right into Egypt.&quot; The verb <em>dābaqlākem</em> (pursue/cling to you) conveys relentless following.</p>",
"17": "<p><strong>wĕhāyû kol-hāʾănāšîm ʾăšer-śāmû pĕnêhem lāboʾ Miṣrayim lāgûr šām</strong> — the comprehensive statement: &quot;All who set their faces to go to Egypt to live there shall die by the sword, famine, and pestilence.&quot; <em>Lāśûm pānîm lĕ-</em> (to set one&apos;s face toward) is the idiom of determined direction. The MKT&apos;s &quot;set their faces&quot; preserves the idiom&apos;s decisiveness.</p>",
"18": "<p><strong>kăʾăšer nittāk ʾappî ûḥămātî ʾel-yōšĕbê Yĕrûšālaim</strong> — &quot;Just as my anger and wrath were poured out on the inhabitants of Jerusalem, so my wrath will be poured out on you when you go to Egypt.&quot; The comparison to Jerusalem&apos;s fate is the most frightening possible warning: what they saw happen to Jerusalem will happen to them in Egypt. <em>Wĕhîytem lĕʾālâ wĕlĕšammâ ûlĕqĕlālâ ûlĕḥerpâ</em> — the fourfold shame vocabulary from 24:9 now applied to the Egypt-bound remnant.</p>",
"19": "<p><strong>dabbēr YHWH ʾălêkem šĕʾērît Yĕhûdâ lōʾ-tābōʾû Miṣrayim</strong> — &quot;The LORD has spoken to you, O remnant of Judah: Do not go to Egypt.&quot; The simplest possible restatement of the prohibition. <em>Yādōaʿ tēdĕʿû kî hăʿîdōtî bākem hayyôm</em> — &quot;Know for certain this day that I have warned you.&quot; The infinitive absolute (<em>yādōaʿ tēdĕʿû</em>) and the prophetic testimony formula make this the clearest possible divine warning.</p>",
"20": "<p><strong>kî hitʿîtem bĕnapsĕšôtêkem</strong> — &quot;For you have been dishonest with yourselves&quot;; the accusation is reflexive — the deceit is self-directed, not just outward dishonesty. <em>Kî ʾattem šĕlaḥtem ʾōtî ʾel-YHWH ʾĕlōhêkem lēʾmōr hitpallēl baʿădēnû</em> — the bad faith: they petitioned YHWH to find out what to do, then the oracle comes and they disobey it. The MKT&apos;s &quot;dishonest with yourselves&quot; renders <em>hitʿîtem bĕnapsĕšôtêkem</em> (you have made your souls err/sin against themselves) — the reflexive form signals self-deception.</p>",
"21": "<p>The indictment stated: &quot;I have declared it to you today, but you have not obeyed the voice of the LORD your God in anything he sent me to tell you.&quot; The final verdict before they act on their intention. The word <em>bĕkōl ʾăšer šĕlaḥānî ʾălêkem</em> (in all/everything he sent me to tell you) is comprehensive — not partial disobedience but total rejection of the oracle.</p>",
"22": "<p><strong>wĕʿattâ yādōaʿ tēdĕʿû kî baḥereb bārāʿāb ûbaddāber tāmûtû</strong> — &quot;Now therefore know for certain that you will die by the sword, by famine, and by pestilence in the place where you want to go to settle.&quot; The oracle closes with the same triple judgment (sword/famine/plague) that has appeared throughout the book as the covenant-curse triad. The MKT renders <em>yādōaʿ tēdĕʿû</em> as &quot;know for certain&quot; (infinitive absolute for emphasis).</p>"
},
"43": {
"1": "<p>The narrative transition: after Jeremiah finishes speaking &quot;all the words of the LORD their God (<em>kol dibrê YHWH ʾĕlōhêhem</em>) — every word the LORD their God had sent him to tell them&quot; — the community&apos;s response is rejection. The redundancy (&quot;all the words... every word&quot;) emphasizes the completeness of the message given; there is no remaining word that could have changed their minds. Rejection of comprehensive prophecy is total rejection.</p>",
"2": "<p><strong>wayyōʾmer ʿAzaryāhû ben-Hôšaʿyāhû... lōʾ šāqer ʾattâ mĕdabbēr</strong> — &quot;Azariah son of Hoshaiah... said to Jeremiah: You are speaking falsely!&quot; <em>Šeqer</em> (falsehood) — the same word Jeremiah used against Hananiah and the false prophets. Now the accusation of false prophecy is turned against the authentic prophet. The MKT renders the blunt accusation: &quot;You are speaking falsely!&quot; The exclamation is appropriate to the direct verbal attack.</p>",
"3": "<p><strong>kî Bārûk ben-Nĕriyyāhû massît ʾōtĕkā bānû</strong> — &quot;But Baruch son of Neriah is inciting you against us, to deliver us into the hands of the Chaldeans.&quot; The scapegoating of Baruch: the accusation that Jeremiah&apos;s secretary is the real source of the anti-Egypt advice. <em>Massît</em> (inciting, stirring up) is the vocabulary used of the adversary who incites disobedience (cf. Deut 13:6). Making Baruch a Chaldean agent redirects blame from YHWH&apos;s word onto a human conspirator.</p>",
"4": "<p><strong>wayyišmaʿ Yôḥānān ben-Qārēaḥ wĕkol-śārê haḥăyālîm wĕkol-hāʿām bĕqôl YHWH</strong> — &quot;So Johanan son of Kareah and all the commanders of the forces and all the people disobeyed the voice of the LORD (<em>lōʾ šāmĕʿû bĕqôl YHWH</em>), refusing to stay in the land.&quot; The word <em>šāmaʿ bĕqôl</em> (obey, listen to the voice) — the covenantal hearing-obedience term — is negated: they did not listen. The MKT renders the refusal directly: &quot;disobeyed the voice of the LORD.&quot;</p>",
"5": "<p>The irony of 43:5: Johanan and the commanders took &quot;the entire remnant of Judah who had returned (<em>šābû</em>) from all the nations where they had been scattered&quot; — those who had <em>returned</em> from exile-like scattering are now led away from the land. The double <em>šûb</em> narrative: people who returned are now being taken away again by those who should have led them home.</p>",
"6": "<p>The list of those taken to Egypt: men, women, children, royal daughters (<em>ʾet-bĕnôt hammelek</em>), and those the Babylonian captain had placed under Gedaliah. The &quot;royal daughters&quot; reappear — the Davidic remnant. Also Jeremiah and Baruch are taken (<em>wĕʾet-Yirmĕyāhû hannābîʾ wĕʾet-Bārûk ben-Nĕriyyāhû</em>). The prophet who warned against Egypt is taken to Egypt — the covenant witness goes with the covenant-breakers.</p>",
"7": "<p><strong>wayyābōʾû ʾerets Miṣrayim kî lōʾ šāmĕʿû bĕqôl YHWH</strong> — &quot;They entered the land of Egypt, because they would not obey the voice of the LORD.&quot; The motive clause is explicit: the refusal to obey is the narrator&apos;s final word on why they came to Tahpanhes. The anti-Exodus is complete: the nation that was brought out of Egypt by YHWH&apos;s mighty hand has returned to Egypt by its own disobedience.</p>",
"8": "<p>The divine word comes to Jeremiah even in Tahpanhes (in Egypt) — YHWH&apos;s presence and speech are not geographically limited to the land of Israel. The oracle that follows is a sign-act (vv. 9-13), one of Jeremiah&apos;s most unusual. The oracle in Egypt parallels the oracles against Egypt in the OAN section (chs. 46), completing the frame.</p>",
"9": "<p><strong>qaḥ bĕyādĕkā ʾăbānîm gĕdōlôt ûṭĕmantām bammeleṭ bammalben</strong> — &quot;Take some large stones in your hands and bury them in the mortar in the brick pavement at the entrance to Pharaoh&apos;s palace in Tahpanhes.&quot; The sign-act: stones hidden in the pavement of Pharaoh&apos;s palace entrance will become the foundation for Nebuchadnezzar&apos;s throne. Jeremiah performs this sign publicly, in front of the Jewish community. The MKT renders &quot;mortar in the brick pavement&quot; following MT&apos;s <em>bammeleṭ bammalben</em>.</p>",
"10": "<p><strong>hinnĕnî šōlēaḥ ûlāqaḥtî ʾet-Nĕbûkadrĕʾṣar melek Bābel ʿabdî</strong> — &quot;I am going to send for Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon, my servant (<em>ʿabdî</em>).&quot; For the third time (25:9; 27:6) Nebuchadnezzar is designated YHWH&apos;s servant — the most theologically shocking claim in Jeremiah&apos;s international theology. The pagan conqueror performs YHWH&apos;s will. &quot;He will place his throne above these stones I buried&quot; — the Babylonian king will unknowingly sit on the stones Jeremiah buried. The sign-act creates a covenant connection between the prophet&apos;s action and the future historical event.</p>",
"11": "<p>The comprehensive judgment on Egypt: <em>ʾăšer lammāwet lammāwet wĕʾăšer laššĕbî laššĕbî wĕʾăšer laḥereb laḥereb</em> — &quot;those destined for death, to death; those destined for captivity, to captivity; those destined for the sword, to the sword&quot; — the fourfold formula from 15:2 applied now to Egypt. The Jews who fled to Egypt for safety will encounter there the same covenant judgment they fled.</p>",
"12": "<p><strong>wĕhiṣṣattî ʾēš bĕbāttê ʾĕlōhê Miṣrayim</strong> — &quot;I will set fire to the temples of the gods of Egypt.&quot; The Egyptian gods in their temples will be burned. The image of Nebuchadnezzar picking Egypt clean &quot;as a shepherd picks his garment clean of lice&quot; (<em>kĕhitʿaṭṭôp hārōʿeh ʾet-bigdô</em>) — a colloquial image for thoroughness. The MKT preserves the homely simile as a marker of the oracle&apos;s confident tone.</p>",
"13": "<p><strong>wĕšibbar ʾet-maṣṣĕbôt Bêt-Šemeš ʾăšer bĕʾerets Miṣrayim</strong> — &quot;He will demolish the sacred pillars of Beth-shemesh (<em>Bêt-Šemeš</em> = &apos;house of the sun&apos;) in the land of Egypt.&quot; Beth-shemesh in Egypt is Heliopolis — the great temple of the sun-god Ra. The destruction of Ra&apos;s sacred pillars (obelisks) by Babylon is the theological climax: even the greatest sun-worship center of the ancient world will fall before YHWH&apos;s instrument. The MKT&apos;s &quot;Beth-shemesh&quot; preserves the Hebrew name that means &quot;House of the Sun.&quot;</p>"
},
"44": {
"1": "<p>The oracle addresses all Jews throughout Egypt — four geographic areas: Migdol (northeast delta), Tahpanhes (northern delta, where the remnant fled), Noph (Memphis, central Egypt), and Pathros (<em>paṭrôs</em>, Upper Egypt — the south). The comprehensive geographic sweep indicates a substantial Jewish diaspora already in Egypt before the post-fall remnant arrived. The oracle is pan-Egyptian, not limited to the Tahpanhes colony.</p>",
"2": "<p><strong>ʾattem rĕʾîtem ʾēt kol-hārāʿâ ʾăšer hēbēʾtî ʿal-Yĕrûšālaim</strong> — &quot;You have seen all the disaster I brought on Jerusalem and all the cities of Judah.&quot; The oracle begins with the witnessed evidence: they saw Jerusalem destroyed. <em>Wĕhinnām ḥorbâ hayyôm hazzeh wĕʾên yôšēb bāhem</em> — &quot;and they lie desolate this day, with no one living in them.&quot; The desolation is presented as visible, present, and irrefutable.</p>",
"3": "<p><strong>mippĕnê rāʿātām ʾăšer ʿāśû lĕhaʿăsîsēnî lāleket lĕqaṭṭēr laʿăbōd lēʾlōhîm ʾăḥērîm</strong> — &quot;because of the wickedness they committed, provoking me to anger by going to burn offerings to other gods — gods that neither they nor you nor your ancestors had known.&quot; The repetition &quot;neither they nor you nor your ancestors&quot; (<em>hēmmâ wĕʾattem wĕʾăbôtêkem</em>) is comprehensive across time. The gods are defined by their unknownness: they are not the God of the covenant, not the God of Israel&apos;s history.</p>",
"4": "<p><strong>wĕʾešlaḥ ʾălêkem ʾet-kol-ʿăbādây hannĕbîʾîm haškēm wĕšālôaḥ</strong> — &quot;Yet I sent you all my servants the prophets, again and again, urgently (<em>haškēm wĕšālôaḥ</em>).&quot; The infinitive absolute construction (<em>haškēm wĕšālôaḥ</em>, rising early and sending) conveys persistent, urgent repetition — the standard Jeremianic formula for YHWH&apos;s comprehensive prophetic effort. <em>ʾAl-tāʿăśû ʾet-haddebet hammĕtôrāʿâ hazzōʾt ʾăšer śānēʾtî</em> — &quot;Do not do this detestable thing that I hate&quot; — YHWH&apos;s stated emotional response to the idolatry: hatred of the detestable.</p>",
"5": "<p><strong>wĕlōʾ šāmĕʿû wĕlōʾ hiṭṭû ʾet-ʾoznām lāšûb mērāʿātām</strong> — &quot;But they did not listen or pay attention, to turn from their wickedness and stop making offerings to other gods.&quot; The refrain of non-listening (<em>lōʾ šāmĕʿû wĕlōʾ hiṭṭû ʾet-ʾoznām</em>) runs throughout Jeremiah (7:24, 11:8, 17:23, 25:4). The covenant hearing-obedience formula negated: they had ears but did not incline them. The MKT preserves &quot;did not listen or pay attention&quot; as two distinct acts of covenant failure.</p>",
"6": "<p><strong>wayyittāk ʾappî ûḥămātî wattibʿar bĕʿārê Yĕhûdâ</strong> — &quot;Therefore my wrath and my anger were poured out and ignited in the cities of Judah.&quot; The spatial progression — cities of Judah → streets of Jerusalem — traces the covenant judgment from the periphery to the center. The result: &quot;they became the desolation and waste that they are today&quot; (<em>lĕḥorbâ ûlišmāmâ kayyôm hazzeh</em>). The present-tense desolation is the evidence for the past judgment and the warning about the future.</p>",
"7": "<p><strong>wĕʿattâ kōh-ʾāmar YHWH ʾĕlōhê ṣĕbāʾôt ʾĕlōhê Yiśrāʾēl</strong> — the transition to direct address. <em>Lāmâ ʾattem ʿōśîm rāʿâ gĕdôlâ ʾel-napšôtêkem</em> — &quot;Why are you doing this great harm to yourselves?&quot; The harm of idolatry is self-harm (<em>ʾel-napšôtêkem</em>, to your own souls). The vocabulary of covenant suicide: cutting off man and woman, child and infant from Judah — leaving no remnant (<em>lĕbiltî hišʾîr lākem šĕʾērît</em>).</p>",
"8": "<p><strong>lĕhaʿăsîsēnî bĕmaʿăśê yĕdêkem lĕqaṭṭēr lēʾlōhîm ʾăḥērîm bĕʾerets Miṣrayim</strong> — &quot;You provoke me to anger with your own handiwork by burning offerings to other gods in the land of Egypt.&quot; <em>Lĕmaʿan hikrît lākem ûlĕmaʿan hĕyôtkem lĕqĕlālâ ûlĕḥerpâ bĕkōl gôyê hāʾārets</em> — the terrible irony: the intent of their idol-worship was security and blessing; the result is to make themselves a curse and reproach among all nations.</p>",
"9": "<p><strong>hăšĕkaḥtem ʾet-rāʿôt ʾăbôtêkem</strong> — &quot;Have you forgotten the wickedness of your ancestors?&quot; The memorial function of covenant history: the past wickedness and its consequences should be remembered as warning. The list: ancestors, kings of Judah, their wives, your own wickedness, the wickedness of your wives — comprehensive across time and gender. The MKT preserves the parallel structure of the comprehensive list.</p>",
"10": "<p><strong>lōʾ dukkaʾû ʿad hayyôm hazzeh</strong> — &quot;They have not been humbled even to this day.&quot; <em>Dākaʾ</em> (be crushed, humbled, broken) — not broken by the disasters they have witnessed. <em>Wĕlōʾ yārĕʾû wĕlōʾ hālĕkû bĕtôrātî ûbĕḥuqqôtay ʾăšer nātattî lĕpânêkem ûlĕpĕnê ʾăbôtêkem</em> — the three covenant-failure verbs: did not fear, did not walk in the Torah, did not keep the statutes. The MKT renders the full triad.</p>",
"11": "<p><strong>hinnĕnî śōmēm ʾet-pānay bākem lĕrāʿâ</strong> — &quot;I am going to set my face against you for disaster&quot; — YHWH&apos;s face turned in judgment rather than blessing. <em>Ûlĕhakrît ʾet-kol-Yĕhûdâ</em> (to cut off all Judah) — the remnant-cutting-off oracle. The remnant in Egypt is not the seed of restoration; it is the object of the final judgment on the covenant community that chose Egypt.</p>",
"12": "<p><strong>wĕlāqaḥtî ʾet-šĕʾērît Yĕhûdâ ʾăšer śāmû pĕnêhem lāboʾ ʾerets Miṣrayim</strong> — &quot;I will take the remnant of Judah who resolved to go to Egypt to live there, and they shall all be consumed.&quot; The twofold fate: <em>baḥereb ûbārāʿāb yittammû</em> (by sword and famine they shall be finished). The series of shame-vocabulary: <em>lĕqĕlālâ lĕʾālâ lĕḥerpâ lĕḥerpâ</em> — curse, waste, horror, reproach. Each noun represents a social dimension of the covenantal humiliation.</p>",
"13": "<p>The parallel with Jerusalem is explicit: <em>kĕʾăšer pāqadtî ʿal-Yĕrûšālaim</em> (as I punished Jerusalem). The Egypt exiles will experience exactly what they watched happen to Jerusalem. The three agents — sword, famine, plague — recur for the last time in Jeremiah&apos;s Egyptian ministry as the covenant-curse triad.</p>",
"14": "<p><strong>wĕlōʾ yihyeh pālîṭ ûśārîd lišʾērît Yĕhûdâ habbāʾîm lāgûr šām bĕʾerets Miṣrayim</strong> — &quot;None of the remnant of Judah who have come to Egypt to live there will escape or survive to return to the land of Judah&quot;; the word <em>pālîṭ</em> (escapee) and <em>śārîd</em> (survivor) — the vocabulary of those who narrowly survived disaster. &quot;Which they long to return to and live in&quot; — the tragic irony: they long for the land but will die without reaching it, because they fled the land.</p>",
"15": "<p>The community&apos;s counter-response: the men who knew their wives had been making offerings to the queen of heaven, &quot;and all the women standing there — a large assembly&quot; (<em>qāhāl gādôl</em>). The formal assembly that petitioned YHWH in 42:1 is now the assembly that formally rejects the oracle. The MKT preserves &quot;large assembly&quot; to maintain the deliberate contrast with the assembly that seemed to commit to obedience.</p>",
"16": "<p><strong>haddābār ʾăšer dibbartā ʾēlênû bĕšēm YHWH ʾênennû šōmĕʿîm ʾēlêkā</strong> — &quot;As for the word you have spoken to us in the name of the LORD, we will not listen to you.&quot; The formal rejection of the prophetic word using the standard oracle-reception formula but negated: &quot;in the name of the LORD&quot; (<em>bĕšēm YHWH</em>) is acknowledged, then rejected. The rejection is not of Jeremiah&apos;s personal opinion but of YHWH&apos;s named word.</p>",
"17": "<p><strong>kî ʿāśôh naʿăśeh ʾet-kol-hadddābār ʾăšer-yāṣāʾ mippînû lĕqaṭṭēr limlekhḗt haššāmayim</strong> — &quot;We will do everything we vowed — making offerings to the queen of heaven (<em>melekhḗt haššāmayim</em>) and pouring out drink offerings to her&quot;; the queen of heaven — the astral goddess Astarte/Ishtar/Inanna — whose cult was deeply embedded in popular Judean religion (cf. 7:18). The community&apos;s argument: when we worshipped her, we had plenty and were not in danger; when we stopped, disaster followed.</p>",
"18": "<p>The theological logic of the community&apos;s argument: <em>ûmiddê ḥādalnû lĕqaṭṭēr limlekhḗt haššāmayim... ḥāsarnû kōl wabbahhereb ûbārāʿāb tāmnû</em> — &quot;since we stopped making offerings to the queen of heaven, we have had nothing and have perished by sword and famine.&quot; The empirical argument: the correlation between stopping the cult and experiencing disaster. This is a genuine and serious theological objection — the community is offering a post-hoc explanation of their historical suffering that inverts Jeremiah&apos;s explanation.</p>",
"19": "<p>The women clarify: we offered to the queen of heaven &quot;without our husbands&apos; knowledge (<em>hamibbalʿadê ʾanšênû</em>)?&quot; — implying the husbands were participants. The women&apos;s defense of the cult and their claim to have made the offerings with household sanction shows this was communal, not clandestine. The MKT renders the women&apos;s speech as direct address to establish their public accountability for the argument.</p>",
"20": "<p><strong>wayyōʾmer Yirmĕyāhû ʾel-kol-hāʿām ʿal-hāʾănāšîm wĕʿal-hanāšîm</strong> — Jeremiah addresses the whole assembly — men and women both. The comprehensive address mirrors the comprehensive rejection (vv. 15-19). Jeremiah does not address one gender more than the other; the oracle applies to all who made or approved the offerings.</p>",
"21": "<p><strong>hălōʾ ʾet-haqqĕṭer ʾăšer qiṭṭartem bĕʿārê Yĕhûdâ</strong> — &quot;The offerings you made in the cities of Judah and the streets of Jerusalem — you and your ancestors, your kings and your officials, and the people of the land — did not the LORD remember them?&quot; YHWH&apos;s counter-argument: yes, YHWH remembered those offerings — and that is exactly why judgment fell. The community&apos;s argument (we sacrificed and prospered) is inverted: you sacrificed and YHWH was angry; the prosperity ended because of the offerings, not despite the lack of them.</p>",
"22": "<p><strong>wĕlōʾ-yūkal YHWH ʿôd śĕʾēt mippĕnê rōaʿ maʿălĕlêkem</strong> — &quot;The LORD could no longer endure your evil deeds and the abominations you committed.&quot; The language of divine exhaustion: YHWH could bear it no longer (<em>lōʾ-yūkal śĕʾēt</em>). This is not a limitation of YHWH&apos;s power but of YHWH&apos;s patience — the divine long-suffering reaching its limit (cf. 2 Chr 36:16: &quot;until the wrath of the LORD arose against his people until there was no remedy&quot;). The MKT renders &quot;could no longer endure&quot; to convey the exhausted-patience meaning.</p>",
"23": "<p>The rebuttal completed: <em>yaʿan ʾăšer qiṭṭartem... ʿal-kēn qārʾat ʾetkem hārāʿâ hazzōʾt</em> — &quot;Because you burned offerings and sinned against the LORD... therefore this disaster has befallen you.&quot; The causal chain runs opposite to the community&apos;s version: not &quot;we stopped offerings and disaster came&quot; but &quot;you burned offerings and disaster came.&quot;</p>",
"24": "<p>Jeremiah&apos;s formal re-address: &quot;Hear the word of the LORD, all you of Judah who are in the land of Egypt.&quot; The shift to the feminine plural (<em>kol-Yĕhûdâ wĕkol-hanāšîm</em>) in the following oracle (v.25) shows the women are specifically addressed for their leading role in the queen of heaven cult (vv. 17-19). The MKT preserves the shift in address as theologically significant.</p>",
"25": "<p><strong>kōh-ʾāmar YHWH ṣĕbāʾôt ʾĕlōhê Yiśrāʾēl lēʾmōr ʾattem wĕnĕšêkem</strong> — the ironic &quot;permission&quot; oracle: &quot;You and your wives have stated with your mouths and fulfilled with your hands: &apos;We will surely keep our vows...&apos; Go ahead, fulfill your vows!&quot; YHWH releases them to fulfill their idolatrous vows — but the release is not a blessing; it is the withdrawal of covenant protection that makes the vow-keeping its own punishment. The MKT renders the ironic imperative: &quot;Go ahead, then, fulfill your vows!&quot;</p>",
"26": "<p><strong>nišbaʿtî bišmî haggādôl ʾāmar YHWH</strong> — &quot;I have sworn by my great name, says the LORD&quot;; the highest oath form available — YHWH swears by himself (cf. Gen 22:16; Isa 45:23; Heb 6:13). &quot;My name will no longer be invoked by any person of Judah anywhere in Egypt&quot; — the covenant-name relationship is severed. The community that rejected YHWH&apos;s word will lose access to YHWH&apos;s name. The MKT renders the divine self-oath solemnly: &quot;sworn by my great name.&quot;</p>",
"27": "<p><strong>hinnĕnî šōqēd ʿălêhem lĕrāʿâ wĕlōʾ lĕṭôbâ</strong> — &quot;I am watching over them for harm, not for good.&quot; The verb <em>šōqēd</em> (watching, alert) here reverses the positive watching of 1:12 (YHWH watches over his word to perform it for good). The same watchful alertness that maintained the covenant promise now maintains the covenant curse. <em>Kōl ʾîš Yĕhûdâ... yittammû</em> — all the men of Judah in Egypt will be consumed.</p>",
"28": "<p>The remnant-within-a-remnant: a few (<em>mĕtê mispar</em>, men of number = a countable few) will return from Egypt to Judah. This exception maintains the possibility of a return and future; even in the judgment oracle, a remnant-principle survives. They will know whose word stands — YHWH&apos;s or the community&apos;s counter-claim. The MKT renders <em>mĕtê mispar</em> as &quot;only a few&quot; — countable rather than countless.</p>",
"29": "<p><strong>wĕzōʾt lākem hāʾôt nĕʾum-YHWH kî-pōqēd ʾănî ʿălêkem</strong> — &quot;This will be your sign, declares the LORD, that I will punish you in this place.&quot; A sign oracle that points to a verifiable future event. The purpose of the sign: <em>lĕmaʿan tēdĕʿû kî qôm yāqûmû dĕbāray ʿălêkem lĕrāʿâ</em> — &quot;so you may know that my words of judgment against you will surely stand.&quot; The <em>qôm yāqûm</em> (surely stand) mirrors Jeremiah&apos;s credibility test for true prophecy in 28:9.</p>",
"30": "<p><strong>hinnĕnî nōtēn ʾet-Parʿōh Ḥopraʿ melek Miṣrayim bĕyad ʾōyĕbāyw</strong> — &quot;I am going to hand over Pharaoh Hophra king of Egypt to his enemies and to those who seek his life, just as I handed over Zedekiah king of Judah.&quot; The explicit parallel: Hophra/Egypt = Zedekiah/Judah. The fate of the Egyptian king will mirror the fate of the Judean king — historical verification of the oracle. Hophra (Apries) was indeed killed in a revolt c. 570 BC, within Jeremiah&apos;s likely lifetime. The MKT preserves &quot;just as I handed over Zedekiah&quot; as the precise comparative.</p>"
},
"45": {
"1": "<p>Chapter 45 is temporally displaced: <em>bašššānâ hārĕbîʿît lîhôyāqîm ben-Yōšiyyāhû</em> — the fourth year of Jehoiakim (605 BC), when Baruch wrote Jeremiah&apos;s dictated scroll. This is the same year as the scroll incident in ch. 36. Placed after the Egypt narrative (chs. 43-44), this oracle functions as a retrospective word to Baruch — a word that applies to his entire ministerial career alongside Jeremiah. The temporal displacement is intentional: the oracle to Baruch closes the prose biographical section before the oracles against the nations begin in ch. 46.</p>",
"2": "<p><strong>kōh ʾāmar YHWH ʾĕlōhê Yiśrāʾēl ʾēlêkā Bārûk</strong> — the divine oracle addressed personally to Baruch. Throughout Jeremiah, Baruch appears as the indispensable but unnamed collaborator — secretary, reader, witness. Here YHWH addresses him directly, acknowledging his individual existence before the covenant God. The address is intimate: <em>ʾēlêkā</em> (to you) — to you specifically, Baruch.</p>",
"3": "<p><strong>ʾāmartā ʾôy-nāʾ lî kî-yāsap YHWH yāgôn ʿal-maḵʾōbî</strong> — &quot;You said: Woe is me! For the LORD has added sorrow to my pain. I am weary with my groaning, and I find no rest.&quot; Baruch&apos;s lament is quoted back to him by YHWH — YHWH has been listening to Baruch&apos;s private complaint. <em>Yāgôn ʿal-maḵʾōbî</em> (sorrow added to my pain) — the accumulation: pain already exists and YHWH adds more. The MKT renders the lament in first person to preserve the emotional directness of Baruch&apos;s complaint.</p>",
"4": "<p><strong>kōh ʾāmar YHWH hinnēh ʾăšer-bānîtî ʾănî hōrēs</strong> — &quot;Thus says the LORD: What I have built I am tearing down, and what I have planted I am uprooting — this entire land.&quot; The vocabulary of Jeremiah&apos;s commissioning (1:10: <em>linṯôš wĕlinthōs ûlĕhaʾăbîd ûlĕharōs ûlibnet ûlintôaʿ</em>) is recycled in a cosmic scope: what YHWH himself built, YHWH himself tears down. Baruch&apos;s personal suffering is contextualized within the universal divine action: the whole land is being unmade. Personal sorrow is real, but it is proportionate to a cosmically significant moment.</p>",
"5": "<p><strong>wĕʾattâ tĕbaqqēš-lĕkā gĕdōlôt ʾal-tĕbaqqēš</strong> — &quot;And you — are you seeking great things for yourself? Stop seeking them.&quot; The rebuke is gentle but clear: Baruch&apos;s lament conceals an expectation of personal greatness or comfort that the current moment cannot provide. <em>Kî hinnĕnî mēbîʾ rāʿâ ʿal-kol-bāśār</em> — &quot;For I am going to bring disaster on all flesh&quot; — the scope of the judgment is universal; Baruch&apos;s personal ambitions must be surrendered to this reality. The final promise: <em>ûnātattî lĕkā ʾet-napšĕkā lĕšālāl ʾal-kol-hamĕqōmôt ʾăšer tēlēk šām</em> — &quot;but I will give you your life as a prize of war in all the places where you go.&quot; <em>Nepeš lĕšālāl</em> (life as plunder/prize) — life itself, not achievement or recognition, is the promised gift. The MKT renders &quot;your life as a prize of war&quot; preserving the military metaphor: survival when others fall is itself the victory.</p>"
}
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-original', 'jeremiah')
    merge_comm(existing, JEREMIAH)
    save_comm('mkt-original', 'jeremiah', existing)
    print('Jeremiah 41-45 mkt-original written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
